The President of the African Development Bank (AfDB), Dr Akinwunmi Adesina has denied allegation of favoritism leveled against him by some staff of the bank as he expressed strong confidence in the governance systems of the Bank put in place by the Board of Governors of the Bank. Adesina in a press statement issued yesterday said the Ethics Committee of the Board of Directors is following its internal review systems and should be allowed to complete its review and work without interference from anyone or the media. An investigation is underway at the AfDB as regards accusation by a fringe of staff of favoritism for the benefit of relatives compatriots and “unethical” behavior. The suspicions also relate to cases of “violation of the code of conduct” and of “hindering efficiency affecting confidence in the integrity” of the Bank. While noting that AfDB had been rated the fourth most transparent institution in the world by Publish What You Fund, Adesina said the bank “has a very high reputation of good governance. I am 100 per cent confident that due process and transparency, based on facts and evidence, will indicate that these are all nothing more than spurious and unfounded allegations. “I would like all our highly dedicated Bank staff, shareholders and partners not to be moved or shaken by any of these blatantly false allegations. I will stay calm and resolute. I will not be distracted. No amount of lies can ever cover up the truth. Soon the truth will come out. “I will continue to discharge my duties and responsibilities as President, with the highest level of professionalism, dedication and unshaken resolve, to lead and support the Bank’s bold mission for Africa’s accelerated development, and to help protect the continent at this time of the COVID19 pandemic.” 